<section id="eip-186"><title>Experiment : Current in Series Circuits</title><para id="id66871">
          <title>Aim:</title>To determine the effect of multiple resistors on current in a circuit</para>
        <para id="id66886">
          <title>Apparatus:</title>
        <list id="id66895" display="block" list-type="bulleted">
          <item id="uid49">Battery
</item>
          <item id="uid50">Resistors
</item>
          <item id="uid51">Light bulb
</item>
          <item id="uid52">Wires
</item>
        </list></para>
        <para id="id66948">
          <title>Method:</title>
        <list id="id66957" display="block" list-type="enumerated">
          <item id="uid53">Construct the following circuits
<figure id="id66976"><media id="id66976_media" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/PG10C9_027.png" id="id66976_onlineimage" width="334"/><image mime-type="application/postscript" for="pdf" src="../../media/PG10C9_027.eps" id="id66976_printimage"/></media></figure></item>
          <item id="uid54">Rank the three circuits in terms of the brightness of the bulb.
</item>
        </list></para>
        <para id="id66996">
          <title>Conclusions:</title>
        The brightness of the bulb is an indicator of how much current is flowing. If the bulb gets brighter because of a change then more current is flowing. If the bulb gets dimmer less current is flowing.
You will find that the more resistors you have the dimmer the bulb.
 </para>

